<TITLE> Congress, ally continue bickering </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Apr 22 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The following is a snapshot of recent developments in India's general election campaign. (The sources are mentioned in brackets). The rift between the Congress and its regional ally Rashtriya Janata Dal (RJD) seems to be widening. After failing to agree to a seat-sharing arrangement in Bihar where the RJD is strong, Congress leader and Foreign Minister Pranab Mukherjee warned RJD chief Lalu Prasad that he may not become a minister if the Congress-led coalition comes to power. (All newspapers) RJD is part of the Congress-led coalition. Prasad retorted by saying that Prime Minister Manmohan Singh was the Congress choice for the top job and not the coalition's. He said the coalition partners would sit down and pick a leader to be the prime minister after the election. The Hindu-nationalist opposition Bharatiya Janata Party has said it would identity up to 100 infrastructure projects of national importance. Releasing a document outlining the party's plans on infrastructure, the BJP said it would build 20 km of roads every day if voted to power. (The Economic Times
